							<h1>Summer Fair</h1>
                            <audio src="/audionew/en/SummerFair.mp3" controls>
                                    Recording of SUmmer Fair's article
                            </audio>
                            <p>
                                <br>
                                Even among American Chinatowns, Chicago has a unique character of its own. One of the best examples of this is the annual Summer Fair occurring in July. The Fair began in the summer of 1979 as a 'Taste of Chinatown', and has happened annually every year since.
                                <br> <br />
                                The Summer Fair had originally begun as a cultural event and art fair with plenty of entertainment as a “Taste of Chinatown”. William Fong, Charlie Soo, and the entire Cheung family, relatives and friends, donated their own money and time for the first three years of the fair's existence, which included the first Chinatown 5K run. This event was born to promote Chinatown and organizations such as The Chinese American Civic Council, Chinatown Chamber of Commerce, and others a chance to work together for the greater good of Chinatown. It was also adopted by Mayor Jane Byrnes in its birth year by her, “Summertime in Chicago”. Ten years later Alderman Fred B. Roti directed Gene Lee to form the Chinatown Special Events to produce fair and community-wide events like it every year. Then in 2014, they joined up with Chicago Chinatown Community Foundation to insure the success of the fair and the other events that they produced.
                                <br> <br />
                                Today the fair is an extraordinary event that can be enjoyed by all who visit it. Different vendors come every year to sponsor the fair and put their wares up for sale for those who wish to buy them. If shopping is not what you are looking to do at the festival then there is a variety of shows going on during the day. You can see dance shows from traditional dragon and lion dancing to modern k-pop. There are also fitness shows and martial arts demonstrations to view. No matter what your taste, is the Summer Fair is a wonderful unifying event that is a staple of Chinatown and a joy to take part in.
                            </p>
								
